Export Prohibition and Other Quantitative Restrictions
Non quantitative, non discriminatory measures (domestic regulation)
Unfair use of state help or subsidies
fields.description: Local producers or suppliers receive money or assistance from their government which makes it harder for non-domestic producers and suppliers to compete.

fields.name: Unreasonable import quotas
fields.description: Restrictions on what can be sold in a country which go beyond what is allowed by relevant trade agreements or which seem unjustified.

fields.name: Burdensome customs procedures
fields.description: Requirements that goods go through checks, or provide documentation, which seem to serve no practical purpose.

fields.name: Restrictive government procurement rules and practices
fields.description: Regulations or special requirements which make it difficult or impossible for non-domestic suppliers to compete for a contract.

fields.name: Unreasonable technical regulations, standards and conformity assessment procedures
fields.description: Regulations or processes which don't seem to serve any legitimate purpose, or which discriminate against importers. This can include arbitrary rules around product labelling.

fields.name: Poor protection of intellectual property rights and geographical indicators
fields.description: Instances of piracy, counterfeiting or mis-labelling which undermine legitimate export trade. Geographical indicators include Scotch whisky and Stilton cheese.

fields.name: Legislation on Copyright and Related Rights
Legislation on Appellations of Origin and Geographic Indications
Legislation on Layout Designs of Integrated Circuits
Unreasonable sanitary and phytosanitary measures
fields.description: Measures purporting to protect consumer health, animal and plant welfare or the environment which seem unreasonable.

fields.name: Restrictive rules of origin
fields.description: Demands for evidence of the countries in which a product was produced, even when there seems no reason for the requirement.

fields.name: Barriers to trade in services and investment, such as unjustified foreign ownership caps, joint venture obligations and discriminatory treatment
fields.description: Financial rules which make imported services uncompetitive, or unreasonably discourage foreign investment.

fields.name: Price-control measures, including additional taxes and charges
Restrictions on a country's own exporters
fields.description: Unreasonable export limits designed to keep domestic product prices low and which make it difficult for other countries' exporters to compete.

fields.name: Export Prohibition and Other Quantitative Restrictions
Risk analyses (including PRA - Pest Risk Analyses)
Tariffs and taxes imposed to protect, or favour, local producers
fields.description: Usually charges imposed on imports to make them more expensive than domestically produced goods.

fields.name: Restrictions on access to raw materials
fields.description: Typically, requirements that goods must contain a high proportion of locally produced material.
